{
  "doc_id": "57954",
  "text": "The development and implementation of various symptomatic treatments since cystic fibrosis was first recognized has greatly improved survival. In the 1970s and 1980s pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy and improved nutritional management were introduced [CITATION_1] . In terms of lung disease, removal of mucus and secretions with chest physiotherapy [CITATION_2] and more advanced lung clearance devices and techniques, along with the more recent use of inhaled drugs such as dornase alpha (which helps cleave DNA in the airway from necrotic neutrophils, reducing the tenacity of secretions) [CITATION_3] and hypertonic saline (which works osmotically by increasing the hydration of mucus and ASL), have also been beneficial [CITATION_4] . Furthermore, antimicrobial therapies targeting acute and chronic infection in the form of oral, intravenous and inhaled drugs are critical parts of modern cystic fibrosis treatment [CITATION_5] . The development of specialist centers delivering expert multidisciplinary care in a coordinated fashion has also been crucial in improving outcomes [CITATION_6] . At present, the median life expectancy of patients with cystic fibrosis has increased to nearly 40 years, with projected survival for newborn infants with cystic fibrosis born today beyond the fifth decade of life [CITATION_7] . Genetic testing is a normal part of the diagnostic process, along with measurement of sweat chloride levels as a measure of CFTR function [CITATION_8] .",
